  <section class="section methodology" data-tab="underhood">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header-editorial">
        <div>
          <div class="kicker">Methodology</div>
          <h2>How the numbers are made</h2>
          <p class="caption" style="margin-top: 12px; max-width: 720px;">
            Five formal definitions, each paired with the exact variable in <code>drift_radar.json</code> that computes it. If a claim on any other tab looks surprising, the block below names the line that produced it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="methodology-body">
        <div class="method-block">
          <h3>Cross-model divergence score</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">For each prompt across the three active engines, Drift Radar takes the own-brand visibility on every engine, then combines the range and the Coefficient of Variation into a single score in <code>[0, 1]</code>:</p>
          <pre class="formula">divergence = 0.7 · (max(vis) − min(vis)) + 0.3 · clamp(CV(vis), 0, 2) / 2</pre>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Range dominates – intuitive and bounded. CV adds a secondary smoothed signal for cases where all engines are non-zero but still spread. Scores ≥ 0.30 are flagged as drifting.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-block">
          <h3>Wilson 95 % confidence intervals</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Every visibility fraction is a proportion from a small sample – Peec samples once per day per engine. Drift Radar reports Wilson score confidence intervals for each prompt × engine: three days means <code>n = 3</code>, so bands are wide. Small samples get wide bands; the tool never overstates certainty.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-block">
          <h3>Silence classification</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong class="serif">Own-only silence</strong> – your brand has zero mentions on every engine, and at least one tracked competitor has at least one mention on some engine.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong class="serif">Full silence</strong> – no tracked brand, own or competitor, is mentioned on any engine. The category is answered generically.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-block">
          <h3>Narrative stability extraction</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">For the maximum-drift prompts, Drift Radar calls <code>Claude Haiku 4.5</code> over the full response text from every engine and extracts up to five atomic claims per answer, each categorized as <em>brand</em>, <em>substance</em>, <em>function</em>, <em>condition</em>, or <em>criterion</em>.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">The narrative-mix bar shows claim-type distribution per engine. <em>Brand</em> claims rarely overlap across engines – each model names different products. <em>Substance</em> and <em>criterion</em> claims overlap more often (MSM, Glucosamin, grain-free), because active ingredients and quality markers are closer to settled knowledge. Stable concepts become the anchor for content briefs; divergent ones mark the editorial gaps.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-block">
          <h3>Data source</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Peec AI MCP at <code>api.peec.ai/mcp</code>, OAuth authenticated.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Tools used: <code>list_prompts</code>, <code>list_chats</code>, <code>get_brand_report</code> with <code>dimensions=[prompt_id, model_id]</code>, <code>get_chat</code> for full response text.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Active engines in this snapshot: {active_models.map((m: any) => m.name).join(', ')}.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

